post_text: With a good possibility of storms and no place to shelter, I don’t want to risk students safety. I would rather miss a day of work and be safe than chance it and have students get hurt or ruin equipment. We will move the leadership meeting to Tuesday morning, and just shift the schedule back a day, while still ending on Thursday. If you have an instrument at the school and want to swing by to get a head start on learning the music that is posted, I will be at the school from 10am-noon so you can come pick it up, provided you are masked and we only have a couple students in at a time. See y’all Tuesday!

of band camp is cancelled. See everyone Tuesday.

Thank you!

post_text:
Bill Agresta’s Hemlock Legends Fund was created in honor and memory of Bill Agresta - legendary Coach and Teacher at Hemlock High School. Bill had a tough-love attitude but displayed a deep passion for helping students not only personally, but also financially. He created and distributed hundreds of scholarships honoring other influential educators and leaders in the Hemlock community. "Wild Bill" raised funds through selling candy bars and pop and collecting pop cans for deposit returns. In order to fulfill the constantly moving shoes of this legendary man and his mission, this fund will be established as an endowment at the Saginaw Community Foundation where it will be able to continue to grant out scholarships to HHS students yearly as Bill did, honoring all the individuals that Bill had honored, and more. Our hope is that this endowment will continue to grow to become a permanent place for honor and memory of the "Legends" of the Hemlock Community.

A very special thanks to HHS alum Kendra Kempf who processed this through the SCF so quickly.

Bill Agresta's Hemlock Legends Fund - Saginaw Community Foundation

post_text:
Running with the Angels

Many of you may already know, but it is with a heavy heart that we share the news that the Huskie Pack lost one of its most beloved in the earlier hours of yesterday. Bill Agresta was a beloved teacher, coach, friend, and champion of students. He now runs with the Angels.

He was an enduring fixture at our high school long after his retirement from teaching, where he could be often found collecting and organizing cans for student scholarship funds that he worked to generate and distribute annually. They don't make them like Bill anymore, he was surely a one of a kind and will be missed by all that knew him.

When we have more information we will share it with you.

Hemlock Middle School
May 31 at 1:31 PM ·

Parents and students--It's time to return Chromebooks & chargers, textbooks, library books, etc. We want to see you off to summer vacation in person. All items belonging to the school can be returned on Thursday evening, June 4 between 6-7 PM or Friday, June 5, between 10 AM and 2 PM. Drive up to our front doors, stop at the curb, stay in your vehicle, and be ready to hand off your items to a staff member--several of us will be there to take care of you and to see you off for the summer. If neither of those options work for you, we can schedule a visit at a different time. Contact Mr. Keyser at keyser@hemlockps.com if necessary. Those who would need to keep their Chromebooks to complete summer school classes will have a different collection time.

post_text: The home of the Huskies has turned into a home for those impacted by the flooding in our area. Last night, we housed 50+ people within the high school and many more in campers and in the parking lot. Right now, we are all set with toiletries (thanks, Sam Turner, Haltom family, and others), perishable goods, and meals for the day. We will accept non-perishable items like bottled water, snacks, etc. but right now it looks like we have enough to get us through the day. If you would like more information please contact our office (989) 642-5282 and leave a message and we will get back to you as we are able. Many thanks to all the individuals and organizations that have helped us help people in need. Stay safe, stay healthy. #HHS #UnitedWay #MWC #OLLI #PTO #huskietastic #since1863 #bettertogether

post_text:
Tune in to this episode of the Huskie Pack Pod Cast to listen into a conversation between Motivational Speaker and Leader, Brian Pruitt and Superintendent Killingbeck.

Brian Pruitt Motivational was started in 1994 by its founder Brian Pruitt. Brian is a former All-American athlete, author and entrepreneur. He discovered that people could accomplish just about anything if they had the right perspective, took the right approach, lived by the right principles and walked through the appropriate process. He has traveled across the United States and other countries equipping listeners with the tools to overcome obstacles to accomplish their dreams. Audiences have been rejuvenated to run after their dreams as they discovered that those obstacles could be defeated.

Brian Pruitt Motivational has impacted the lives of people around the world. BPM speaking engagements vary from School Assemblies, Businesses, Churches, Youth Organizations, Sports Teams, and Non-Profit Organizations.

Please like and share to help get the word out to children and parents in need.

Our foodservice made a gazillion salads to provide nutritional meals to students 18 and under or individuals with disabilities up to age 26. We have drive-up pick up from 10 AM -12 noon on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday on the Eastside of Hemlock Middle School at door #29 and deliveries upon request (989) 642-4700. Note 287 = gazillion or 1 rack of salads.

post_text: Each year, the TVC honors the top three academic achievers from each school. This distinction is based on a combination of GPA and SAT score. Typically a banquet is held in April, but obviously, that was not possible this year. We are pleased to be able to recognize these outstanding academic achievers in this digital format, and we congratulate them on all of their accomplishments and all that awaits them in their bright futures. WTG, Seth Burns, Jonathan Turnipseed, and Hannah Killingbeck! #Classof2020 #huskietastic #since1863

Hemlock High School
April 16 at 5:00 PM ·

This is Hemlock Huskie aka "Hemmie". He is sad. He misses all the kids, teachers and staff. It is quiet and lonely at the school.

It is ok to be sad sometimes. But just know that there are people around that care about you. Like the people at your school. If you need someone to talk to, reach out to a teacher, administrator or staff member. We are here for you.

Even though we are #hemlockstrong, everyone needs someone sometimes.

We recently launched the Hemlock Hub for distant learning to better support our students, parents, and staff as we work together to provide the best possible education given our current circumstances.

The hub provides a K-12 snapshot for the weekly learning activities grade K-8 and for each high school teacher. It also has a place to schedule virtual office time with a teacher, social worker or counselor, or building principal.

We will continue to develop the hub and make improvements, visit www.hemlockps.com and click on this picture to visit the Hemlock Hub.

Hemlock Middle School
March 27 at 12:23 PM ·

We had a "virtual staff meeting" this morning with all HMS teachers! It was great to see each of them and hear each other's voices. We all miss being at school and seeing our students and each other. One topic of discussion was "How are our students doing in terms of meeting learning expectations and preparing for the future when we return to school?" The answers varied, but overall our kids are doing very well using online learning. Please remember--there is work to do on the part of both teachers and students to prepare for when we return--we need everyone engaged in learning to make this work. #hemlockteachersonthejobforkidsnomatterwhat #hemlockstudentsarecontinuingtolearn

shared_text:
Hemlock Middle School
March 13 at 4:29 PM ·

Middle school parents--you should be very proud of your kids today. As I met with them today by grade, they could have been grumbling, complaining, negative or simply delirious about having three weeks off. Instead, I talked to kids who were adaptable, who were ready to do whatever they could with this time off to extend their learning, who were positive and looking on the bright side, who were ready to accept this new challenge of complete virtual learning for a couple of weeks. We have great kids at Hemlock Middle School. And terrific teachers and staff as well. AND great parents who support their kids and our staff. Thank you for helping your kids and our teachers to meet this new educational challenge head on. We have much to be proud of. Give your child a pat on the back and a high five today.
